    <title type="text">Art and the Bible</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<div class="tr_bq"><a href="http://www.artbible.info/"><span
      class="sitetitel">Art and the Bible</span></a></div><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><div class="tr_bq"><span class="sitetitel"><img
      alt="http://www.artbible.info/pix/vingers.jpg" class="decoded"
      src="http://www.artbible.info/pix/vingers.jpg" />
      </span></div></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Have you ever found yourself in front of a famous painting
      wondering what it was all about? Imagine if you could know more about the image and the
      artist's treatment of the subject. Wouldn't this add to the beauty of the experience? For your
      pleasure and enlightenment this site offers background information on famous paintings and
      biblical themes. We hope you'll enjoy our effort. </span><br /> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Throughout the history of art great masters have turned to the
      Bible for inspiration. As an near inexhaustible narrative source depicting all conceivable
      aspects of the human condition it allowed the artist to express his piety while getting away
      with murder. And as often as not the work would have been commissioned by a religious
      institute, so that the subject matter was dictated beforehand by the prospective
      buyer.</span><br /> <span style="font-size: x-small;">We have collected
      pictures of hundreds of paintings, famous and less famous, and linked them to their
      corresponding Bible passage - the passage the artist may have read. We've also provided
      information on the paintings themselves.</span><br /> <span style="font-size:
      x-small;">The Bible texts are from the King James Version - the translation ordered by the
      British King James, first published in 1611.</span><br /> <span
      style="font-size: x-small;">This site has been created and is maintained by
